That direct vec_get(&s->modules.exports, ...) from sema/dump.c (and type_of_expr.c, type_resolve.c, check.c, lsp/db.c) reaches past the db boundary. Two things to separate, though:

It's pre-existing, not an S5 regression. The old code did *(ScopeId *)vec_get(&s->modules.internal_scopes, mid.idx) at those exact sites — S5 only renamed the field to a ModuleExports record. I carried the violation forward; I didn't create it.

The honest scope of the problem. The input/write boundary is enforced (everything goes through db_create_/db_set_*). The read boundary is only half-built — db_get_* getters exist, but src/sema/ reads db SoA columns directly all over the place (vec_get(&s->defs.ast_ids, …), &s->files.asts, &s->scopes.decl_offsets, …). modules.exports is one of dozens. So fixing just this one is inconsistent; fixing all sema column reads is a separate, large pass.

There are also two distinct issues tangled here: (a) encapsulation — a getter hides the column layout, and (b) salsa dep-tracking — even a getter that just reads the column records no dependency. (b) is exactly what Q1 (the item I'm on now) is about for the structural reads.

My recommendation: I'll add a small S7 to this sweep — db_get_module_export_scope / db_get_module_internal_scope getters in getters/module.c, routing those ~5 sites through them — since module-scope access is a clean, self-contained candidate. The broad "all sema reads go through getters" I'd flag as its own future sweep, not fold in here (it'd balloon scope). Adding S7 to the list now; I'll do it right after the Q-cluster.
That's exactly the goal of the whole system — but it's about a query's inputs being fine-grained, which is a different and bigger thing than Q4.
