Also one gap: 3.2a (1:1 hardcoded) and 3.3 (no module-assignment policy) are the same problem — oredb_typecheck always mints a singleton module. Plus a sub-gap you didn't list: when file A imports sibling B and B isn't open in the editor, the LSP must load B from disk — today oredb_did_open only ever sees editor-opened docs. Multi-file modules can't work without on-disk loading of unopened imports. Fold that into B.
I was wrong to flag 2.2 as an open gap — it's essentially already done. lsp_uri_to_path already canonicalizes via realpath():


char resolved[PATH_MAX];
if (realpath(decoded, resolved)) { free(decoded); return strdup(resolved); }
return decoded;  // fallback
realpath resolves .., ., and symlinks for any file that exists on disk — which is every file the editor opens. Your test case (/a/b.ore vs /a/../a/b.ore) already passes today. The header even documents it as intentional.

The one residual hole: the fallback branch. When realpath fails — the file isn't on disk yet — it returns the raw lexically-decoded path with ./.. not collapsed and not absolutized. So a not-yet-saved file could still split identity. But: an LSP didOpen carries a file:// URI for a real opened document, so the file almost always exists; untitled buffers use untitled: URIs which lsp_uri_to_path already rejects. This case is a genuine corner (file deleted-while-open, or a race).

So 2.2 is two-thirds a non-gap and one-third a corner case. Options:

Mark 2.2 done, go to Gap A. Defensible — realpath covers every realistic open.


Also one gap: 3.2a (1:1 hardcoded) and 3.3 (no module-assignment policy) are the same problem — oredb_typecheck always mints a singleton module. Plus a sub-gap you didn't list: when file A imports sibling B and B isn't open in the editor, the LSP must load B from disk — today oredb_did_open only ever sees editor-opened docs. Multi-file modules can't work without on-disk loading of unopened imports. Fold that into B.
